4.5 We recommended and the Management agreed to:
a. Instruct the Petty Cash Custodians to replenish the fund promptly once disbursements reach at least 75 percent of the total Petty Cash Fund;
b. Ensure the necessity to establish sufficient Petty Cash Fund to cover one month of non-recurring, emergency, and petty operational expenses for the agency;
c. Direct the Accountant to properly record and classify the actual expenses incurred in conformity with the Chart of Accounts of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs.
d. Require each requestor of the Petty Cash Fund to prepare a separate Petty Cash Voucher for every individual cash advance request and its corresponding liquidation;
e. Ensure that all transactions are duly supported with invoices/receipts and other requirements in conformity with COA Circular 2012-001 and that the Petty Cash Vouchers are properly filled out, signed and dated to ensure proper documentation and establish accountability. The absence of invoices and other requirements will result to the issuance of Notice of Suspension;
f. Direct the Petty Cash Custodians to
f.1 make sure that the Petty Cash Vouchers are properly filled out such as the names and the dates, and duly signed and approved by the concerned personnel.
f.2 refrain from requesting petty cash advances for their own use to ensure accountability and transparency; and
g. Require the Petty Cash Custodians to fully liquidate their outstanding petty cash advances at the end of the year. Likewise, direct the Accountant to ensure that all actual expenses incurred are promptly and accurately recorded in the books.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all PPE of the agency pursuant to COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
b. Require the Municipal Treasurer/GSO to exclude unserviceable properties in the RPCPPE and prepare the corresponding IIRUP, where these properties should be recorded;
c. Include in the RPCPPE all categories of PPE such as Land, Land Improvements, Road Network and Systems, Infrastructure, Buildings, Other Structures, Machineries, Other PPE and the Construction in Progress accounts; and
d. Direct the Property Officer and the OIC-Accountant to prioritize the reconciliation of PPE in their respective books to establish the accurate balances of various PPE accounts.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
a. Create a Disposal Committee to facilitate the disposal proceedings of unserviceable properties;
b. Exclude unserviceable properties in the RPCPPE and prepare the corresponding IIRUP, where these properties should be recorded;
c. Ensure that all unserviceable items are kept all together in one secure storage area to prevent loss prior to its disposal; and
d. Direct the Appraisal Committee and the Disposal Committee to conduct the appraisal activity for all unserviceable properties and submit the corresponding report and the request for disposal to the Audit Team for indorsement to COA Regional Technical Services Office for proper evaluation; and
e. Cause the disposal of the unserviceable property soonest upon receipt of the result of the COA-TSO to prevent its further deterioration and to realize income therefrom, if found valuable.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
a. Require from the MDRRMO a written justification for the low implementation of PPAs funded by 5 percent LDRRMF;
b. Require the MDRRMO to ensure that all identified and prioritized development PPAs funded by 5 percent LDRRMF are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready;
c. Require the Municipality Engineering Office to expedite execution of infrastructure projects to guarantee the prompt accomplishment of the same;
d. Require the MDRRMO, in coordination with the MEO, to closely monitor and evaluate the implementation of the identified and prioritized development PPAs embodied in the LDRRMFIP, and to address any cause of suspension or problems that would delays the project implementation to ensure delivery of desired benefits to the constituents; and
e. Require the MDRRMO to evaluate the necessity of the identified priority PPAs that remain unimplemented as of year-end, and ascertain the viability of implementation for the ensuing year to better address disaster related concerns of the Municipality of Dumalag.

We recommended and Management agreed to: 

Direct the Municipal Assessor to undertake a general revision of real property assessments every three (3) years as stated in Section 219 of R.A No. 7160;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to undertake efficient and effective strategies to improve collection of RPT;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to avail of the remedies by administrative action through levy on real property or by judicial proceedings to enforce payment from the real property owners of RPT delinquencies as provided in Section 256 of R.A. No. 7160; and 

